5
Together, the moral argument and the argument from personal experience represent attempts to
ground belief in domains beyond the purely physical. They tap into universal human concerns with
right and wrong and the profound sense of meaning and connection that many people feel. While
they may lack the formal deductive structure of cosmological arguments, they offer a powerful and
deeply personal case for theism. Yet, they face formidable challenges from philosophical dilemmas
like the Euthyphro problem and the inherent unreliability of subjective testimony as a basis for
universal truth claims.
The Ontological Argument: A Priori Proof and Its Enduring
Logical Flaws
Among the most intriguing and debated arguments for God's existence is the ontological argument, a
unique proposition that seeks to prove God's existence through pure logic and definition alone,
without recourse to empirical observation. First articulated by St. Anselm of Canterbury in the 11th
century, this argument has provoked centuries of intense philosophical scrutiny, defending it against
persistent and powerful criticisms. Its core ambition—to derive existence from concept—is
simultaneously its greatest strength and its most glaring weakness.
St. Anselm's original formulation, presented in his work Proslogion, defines God as "a being than
which nothing greater can be conceived" . Anselm then reasons that if such a being existed only
in the mind, one could conceive of a greater being—one that exists in reality as well. Since by
definition God is the greatest conceivable being, He must therefore exist in reality; otherwise, He
would not be the greatest conceivable being, leading to a contradiction . This argument employs a
reductio ad absurdum: it assumes the opposite of what it wants to prove (that God exists only in the
understanding) and shows that this assumption leads to a logical impossibility . Over time, the
argument has been reformulated and defended by numerous thinkers. René Descartes offered a
similar version, arguing that existence is a perfection and thus a supremely perfect being (God) must
exist . Later, Alvin Plantinga developed a modal version using the concept of "possible worlds,"
arguing that if it is even possible that a maximally great being (one with omnipotence, omniscience,
and moral perfection in every possible world) exists, then such a being must exist in all worlds,
including our own .
Despite its sophisticated refinements, the ontological argument is widely considered to be fallacious.
The most famous and influential critique comes from Immanuel Kant, who argued that "existence is
not a predicate" or a real property that can be added to a concept . According to Kant, when we
list the attributes of a hundred-pound weight, we describe its properties (e.g., color, material), but
saying it "exists" does not add another property to the list. Applying this to Anselm's argument, Kant
contended that "existence in reality" is not a "great-making" property superior to "existence in the
understanding." It does not make the concept of a thing greater; it merely asserts that the concept
corresponds to something in the world. Therefore, the second premise of Anselm's argument—that
existence in reality is greater than existence in the mind alone—is false, and the entire argument
collapses .
9 15 16
11 13
13
16
12 16
7 9 10
10 17
This criticism is reinforced by other objections. Gaunilo of Marmoutiers, a contemporary of Anselm,
offered a devastating parody by applying the same logic to a "perfect island" . If the argument
worked for God, he reasoned, it would also prove the existence of a perfect island, which is absurd .
Defenders of the ontological argument respond that the concept of God is unique in being a
necessary being, unlike a contingent island, whose greatness can always be increased . However, this
response itself presupposes a controversial metaphysical distinction between necessary and
contingent beings. Other critics, like Norman Malcolm and Charles Hartshorne, have argued that if
God's non-existence is logically impossible, then His existence is necessary . But this moves from
possibility to necessity without adequately addressing the core issue of whether the concept of a
maximally great being is coherent in the first place, a point raised by C. D. Broad and others .
Formal analyses by logicians like Paul Oppenheimer and Edward Zalta have attempted to salvage the
argument by carefully distinguishing between different notions of "being" and "existence," but even
they acknowledge that the argument relies on assumptions that can be contested . Ultimately, the
consensus among scholars is that while the ontological argument represents a remarkable attempt to
prove God's existence through reason alone, its reliance on a questionable premise about existence as
a predicate renders it unsound .
The Problem of Evil: A Central Challenge to Theistic Coherence
The problem of evil is arguably the most powerful and enduring argument against the existence of
the Abrahamic God—an omnipotent, omniscient, and omnibenevolent (all-powerful, all-knowing,
and perfectly good) being. The core of the argument is a logical tension: how can such a God coexist
with the vast amount and intensity of evil and suffering present in the world? If God is willing to
prevent evil but cannot, He is impotent and not omnipotent. If He can prevent it but is unwilling, He
is malevolent and not omnibenevolent. If He is both able and willing, then whence cometh evil? This
ancient argument, attributed to Epicurus, has been advanced by countless thinkers and remains a
primary battleground in the philosophy of religion .
The argument is often framed probabilistically. Philosopher Paul Draper has argued that the high
prevalence of nonbelief, especially given the global distribution of theism, is highly unlikely under
evangelical Christianity, where God supposedly desires universal belief for salvation . Similarly,
Gary Whittenberger, a clinical psychologist, mounts a powerful evidential argument based on the
Holocaust. He structures his argument as a modus tollens: if an omnipotent, omniscient, and
perfectly moral God exists, He would have prevented the Holocaust; the Holocaust occurred;
therefore, God does not exist . Whittenberger rejects responses like the free will defense, arguing
that an all-powerful God could have designed humans to have free will without the capacity for
genocide . He further describes modern theistic responses to the Holocaust as a form of Holocaust
denialism and labels the idea of "divine exceptionalism"—that God is above moral codes—as
irrational special pleading . For Whittenberger, the Holocaust serves as a definitive, brutal
counterexample to the existence of the omniGod .
Theists have developed a variety of responses, collectively known as theodicies, to address this
formidable challenge. One of the most famous is the free will defense, championed by Alvin
10 11
17
11
9
16
14
15 17
6 7
1 7
4
4
