27
Plantinga. This defense distinguishes between logical and evidential problems of evil. It argues that
moral evil (evil resulting from human actions) can be justified by the greater good of libertarian free
will, which allows for genuine love and virtue . However, this defense is often criticized for failing to
account for natural evils, such as earthquakes, tsunamis, and diseases, which are not caused by
human choices . Another major theodicy is John Hick's "soul-making" theodicy, which posits that
suffering is a necessary part of a process that helps individuals develop virtues like courage,
compassion, and resilience, thereby "making" their souls . Other proposed solutions include the
idea that evil increases longing for God (Coakley 2016, Lehe 2004), provides a basis for hope (Cobb
2017), or that faith requires uncertainty (Dumsday 2015) .
While these defenses offer potential explanations, they are not universally accepted. Critics like J.L.
Mackie have argued that the existence of any gratuitous evil—a suffering event that does not
contribute to a greater good—is incompatible with an all-powerful, all-good God . The sheer scale
of suffering, from natural disasters to genocides, seems to many to defy easy explanation. Some
atheists, like Michael Shermer, have pointed out that the extinction of 99.8% of all species that ever
lived is strong evidence against a benevolent creator . Furthermore, the moral character of a deity
who allows such suffering is questioned. Bertrand Russell, for example, found Jesus' belief in eternal
punishment in hell to be cruel and inconsistent with superlative wisdom or goodness, making Him
an inadequate moral role model . In conclusion, the problem of evil poses a profound and
multifaceted challenge to the coherence of theism. While theists have developed sophisticated
theodicies, the persistence of seemingly pointless suffering continues to fuel powerful arguments for
atheism, forcing a continual re-evaluation of the nature and existence of God in light of the world's
undeniable pain.
Divine Hiddenness and the Limits of Human Comprehension
Two closely related arguments challenge theism by focusing not on the external world but on the
internal state of human belief and the very nature of God. The argument from divine hiddenness
contends that if a personal, perfectly loving God existed, His presence would be evident enough to
prevent widespread nonbelief. Simultaneously, the argument from divine incomprehensibility asserts
that the God of classical theism is so radically "other" that He lies beyond the scope of human
reason and language, rendering any positive claim about His existence meaningless. Together, these
arguments target the very intelligibility of theistic belief.
The argument from divine hiddenness, notably formulated by philosopher J.L. Schellenberg, presents
a deductive case. He defines "nonresistant nonbelief" as the state of an individual who lacks belief in
God yet is not intentionally resisting God's influence or desire for a relationship with them .
Schellenberg argues that if a perfectly loving God existed, such nonresistant nonbelievers would not
exist, because a loving parent would ensure their children knew of their love. Since nonresistant
nonbelief clearly exists, Schellenberg concludes that the omniGod of classical theism does not exist
. This argument has been extended by others. Theodore Drange notes the high global prevalence of
nonbelief is unlikely under theism, where God supposedly desires universal salvation . Stephen
Maitzen points to the uneven geographic distribution of theism as unexpected under a loving God .
